Last week, at a meeting of Ministers of the European Space Agency, Poland was adopted by the twentieth member of the European Space Agency as the second country from the countries of the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 September 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated actively in a number of Agency projects over the years to come.
But the road to space in Poland began much earlier.
Even before World War II, Polish enthusiasts had been on a flight to space, but that was not always an understanding.
I recall, for example, the lecture of A. Sternfeld, who, on 6 December 1933, presented to the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory ideas from his innovative work "Introduction to Space."
The ideas of a young engineer (1905) left the audience indifferent, and after a few years Schernfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadovsky was interested in his work.
In 1934, in France, Sternfeld won the Robert Eno-Peltri and André Luis Hirsch Award for "Introduction to Space."
Dr. Jan Gadovsky (1899-1966), referred to above, later became a great astronomy and space activist.
He has published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and has written a number of books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadolsky became a well-known global cosmoist, and his contribution was appreciated, including the fact that one of the craters on the back of the moon was named after him.
As early as 1925, a road-driven railway was built in Poland.
Unfortunately, the author of the idea remained unknown, as did the details of the draft.
It is not even clear that a missile was to be used to disperse or to stop the trolley.
The information about this dress is only known from the press of that era.
Since 1933, Polish artillery has been thinking about rocket arrows.
The study was carried out by the Arms Technology Section, in cooperation with the Professor Metzilov Wolfke and Gustav Mojitsky.
The remaining material shows that the studies have reached the practical test stage.
But with the arrival of the German troops, the work was interrupted.
In 1937, the idea of a photovoltaic fighter missile, proposed by the engineer Rogozinski, was introduced in the specialized press, and next year the work of the Leliva-Kobiblotsky Air and Aircraft Bomb was launched.
Both projects were developed for military use of missile engines.
Before the war itself, all military missile projects were carried out by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated all the work.
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the work ended because of the beginning of the war.
The next scientific work on space was introduced in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, it is mentioned in the November 1954 issue of "Problems," which contains four voluminous articles on astronautics.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotović proposed to organize a society that would engage in space.
At that time, artificial satellite projects were already on the line, and it was clear that space research was a promising industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Society of Astronautics (PEA) has been trying to join the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951) and has become a real member of the International Federation of Astronautics (established in the autumn).
And next year, the first President of the PEA, Kasimej Zarankevich (1902-1959), became Vice-President of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He remained in that position until his very death, which occurred in 1959.
Since 1956, PCA has made a significant contribution to the development of the very successful meteorological missile RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which was the first Polish missile to carry out scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
The missile, capable of reaching a distance of 1,800 m, was about 80 cm long and was less than 5 kg.
An improved version of RM-1A was subsequently built and two-stage RM-2 was tested in the summer of 1959 in the Bledov Desert.
The missile was about 1.4 m long, and its weight was about 11.5 square metres.
The next version of the missile was already able to carry out real scientific work - the RM-34 missile could have reached 14.5 km, and its mission was to monitor the high-wind.
But further development was suspended in 1962.
The first RM-type missile was followed by a Meteor-1 missile developed between 1962 and 1965.
The missile was designed as two-stage, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (defined as Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which were different in size for scientific equipment.
The Meteor-1A missile had an area of 0.4 L, Meteor-1B 0.34 L and Meteor-1C 0.62 L.
The maximum flight range of all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, a Meteor-2 missile was developed at the Aviation Institute and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
Meteor-2, with a start-up weight of 380 kg, was able to bring a useful 10 kg load to a height of about 60 km.
The versions of Meteor-2N and Meteor-3 were then built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland & apos; s accession to COSPAR (Committee on Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of the COSPAR National Committee two years later.
In addition, within the framework of the Interspace programme, Poland had participated in space research on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslav Gershevsky had become the second interastronaut after Vladimir Remek.
