A ceasefire agreement between Israel and the Hamas group could be a fragile foundation for further peace
Is there a lasting peace between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East?
Another round of bloodshed leads to the conclusion that such hopes are futile.
There are rumours that have become common, senseless disputes about who first started; many buildings have been turned into ruins; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis, have been killed; for the first time in the conflict, rockets fired from the Gaza Strip fell in the vicinity of Israel's capital, Tel Aviv, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
