Perhaps as a result, their struggle will become even more bloody than before.
There are, however, reasons for the hope that this deadly impasse will be overcome.
A war without a winner.
At first glance, the situation is not encouraging.
Even if the ceasefire signed on 21 November is implemented, the clashes that took place this week have only strengthened the positions of the security forces on both sides.
The leaders of the Hamas Islamist movement, which took power in the Gaza Strip in 2007, will say that they have forced Israel to retreat despite its losses.
Although some faction leaders have been destroyed and 1.7 million people have been blocked in one of the most densely populated and troubled corners of our planet, Israel has not been able to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is increasing its popularity in the West Bank of the Jordan River, another Palestinian territory currently controlled by the more moderate Fatah movement.
Moreover, Hamas leaders can well conclude that time is working for them.
As the influence of Islamist movements increases in the Arab world, Hamas has new, influential and rich friends.
